Spot and stalk!  I was walking into the stand I hung last week and saw 5 hogs out in the open bottom feeding.  I got the wind right and slipped in as close as I could and waited.  I was about to shoot a smaller boar when this big daddy just popped into one of the shooting lanes.  I ranged him 49.7 , drew back and buried my 50 pin and let her eat.  I heard the “THWACK” that only mechanicals make and knew I hit the hog.  He spun and ran out in the slough and then  all 5 ran right past me within feet.  I immediately took after the hogs and saw this boar go down get up and move off.  I waited a couple hours, went back and he was right there.  Good hit!  The arrow was buried 30 yards past him in a cypress stump.  Im super impressed and jacked to get after mulies!  May take the @hoytbowhunting Satori out in the AM.  I’ll have a YouTube up for this hunt a little later.  Check link in bio!  #hoghunting #downinthebottoms #spotandstalk #bowhunting #easttexas #teamhoytarchery

But I already shot a Robinhood in Practice.  I didn’t want to bust into a fresh Dozen of shafts so we’re gonna start off with 11 and see how far into season that gets me! Travis was toting his new rifle, a .300 Win Mag and he laced a perfect 180 grain @barnesbullets TSX through this boar’s shoulder at about 150 yards, a really incredible shot! I’ve been holding off this week.  There’s  so much to say, but …. I have nothing right Now.  We lost my Mama this past week.  She had a short bout with illness and went to be with the Lord peacefully in her sleep Monday night/ Tuesday morning, she was only 69.  Rest In Peace sweet lady. 2023 marked 40 years since I bought my first compound bow, a Bear Archery, Black Mag from Academy Sports  off of FM 1960 in Houston.  I had saved money for a long time to have enough to get the bow which was $79.00.  I had just enough to get the bow and two arrows and I lost them both almost immediately! It’s been an incredible joyous journey.  I got saved and came to know Jesus as my lord and savior the same summer, so I’ve walked the earth with a bow in my hand and Jesus in my heart since 1983.  I met @muleymojo in 1995 and he signed me with his shop and @hoytbowhunting  in 1998, all of this has impacted my life tremendously and guided me to be the man I am today and I am truly grateful for All!  Here’s to 2024 and to 40 more wonderful years! 🥂

What is the most you’ve ever sacrificed on a bowhunt?  In 2007 I backpacked in six plus miles for a seven day hunt, it was a straight down hike for 4 hours to get down in with approx 55-60 pound pack with Bivy camp and almost 6 hours up and out.  I hunted for a week with no opportunity for  a shot at a bull.  Day 7 came and went and I did not have a bull down.  I was supposed to be home sometime on the 8th or 9th day, no cell service (no cell phone). I had 1/2 of a chocolate protein bar left in my pack and remnants of a spilled pack of trail mix in a pouch in my backpack.  I decided to stay at least two more days, I desired success more than I feared demise.  Knowing I needed to have calories to even continue the hunt, on the evening of the 7th day I gathered grubs from under logs around my Camp.  I had a wad roughy the size of a golf ball,  popped the heads off of them and brought them to a boil with a couple of oz of water.  I melted the protein bar in with the boiling grubs to make a chocolate stew, threw in the the raisins, nuts and two M&Ms from the trail mix and I ate it.  Honestly, not the worst thing I’ve ever ate.  The next morning, Day 8 I arrowed a trout in the stream in the canyon I hunted.  Trashed an arrow and broadhead but I ate.  That afternoon I arrowed a squirrel and a grouse, I cooked both.  I ate the grouse for supper and saved the squirrel for the next morning.  I kept the squirrel in a gallon zip lock baggie that I stored my toilet paper in. I had squirrel for breakfast on the morning of day 9, that evening I called in two bulls and arrowed this 6x5 at 12 yards.  That night I ate elk loin til my belly hurt.  The next morning I hiked out,  called a packer to come get the elk out and I Called my wife.  A few days later I slept in my own bed, beat up, beat down and wiped out but a sense of satisfaction that I’ve not felt before or since.  I’m not sure I’d do any of that again, but I am glad I did it and pushed well beyond my perceived limits when I had the chance.  #bowhunting #backcountry #diy #colorado #elkhunting
